snippet.textDisplay: You are cooking the ram-don wrong. You are not supposed to put the spicy powder with the noodles in the water. You cook the noodles and dried vegi in the water then drain most of the water, add black powder and half pack of spicy powder and mix. No one use dashi in Jajangmyun. mostly use pork broth, pork stock extract or pork stock cube. if you don't have any of them, just use water. I haven't seen anyone using cabbage in Jajangmyun. Most people use potato instead. we don't use udon noodle in Jjambbong. Neaoguri is not a package version of Jjambbong. it is totally different thing.
snippet.textOriginal: You are cooking the ram-don wrong. You are not supposed to put the spicy powder with the noodles in the water. You cook the noodles and dried vegi in the water then drain most of the water, add black powder and half pack of spicy powder and mix. No one use dashi in Jajangmyun. mostly use pork broth, pork stock extract or pork stock cube. if you don't have any of them, just use water. I haven't seen anyone using cabbage in Jajangmyun. Most people use potato instead. we don't use udon noodle in Jjambbong. Neaoguri is not a package version of Jjambbong. it is totally different thing.

snippet.textDisplay: in asia we do not put the seasoning into the noodles until it has been thoroughly drained, otheriwise it just gets washed away, watching you pour the seasoning into the noodles while it was cooking made me cringe so hard since you just wasted all of its flavor. also, the meat is supposed to be cut into roughly 5 x 2 inch & 1/2 inch thick strips, this gives the seasoning more surface area to penetrate the meat and also helps cook the meat faster.
